label.value: suppression by virus of host translation initiation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of host translation initiation, the host process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein.

label.value: proteolysis by virus of host translation initiation factor

definition.value: The chemical reactions and pathways performed by a virus resulting in the hydrolysis of a host translation initiation factor by cleavage of its peptide bonds.

label.value: suppression by virus of host translation initiation factor activity by induction of host protein dephosphorylation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of activity of a host translation initiation factor by promoting dephosphorylation of a host protein.

label.value: suppression by virus of host translation initiation factor activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of activity of a host translation initiation factor.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-1 symmetry. The T-eq-1 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-2 symmetry. The T-eq-2 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric dimers.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-3 symmetry. The T-eq-3 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 20 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with pseudo T-eq-3 symmetry. The T-eq-pseudo3 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 20 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-4 symmetry. The T-eq-4 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 30 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-7 symmetry. The T-eq-7 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 60 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-13 symmetry. The T-eq-13 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 120 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-16 symmetry. The T-eq-16 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 150 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-25 symmetry. The T-eq-25 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 240 hexameric capsomeres.
The outer layer of a double or triple concentric icosahedral capsid. Outer capsids are part of reoviridae and cystoviridae virions.
The inner layer of a double or triple concentric icosahedral capsid. Inner capsids are part of reoviridae and cystoviridae virions.
The intermediate layer of a triple concentric icosahedral capsid. Intermediate capsids are part of reoviridae virions.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-147 symmetry. T-eq-147 icosahedral capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 1460 hexameric capsomeres for a total of 8820 capsid proteins.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-169 symmetry. T-eq-169 icosahedral capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 1680 hexameric capsomeres for a total of 10140 capsid proteins.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-219 symmetry. T-eq-219 icosahedral capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 2180 hexameric capsomeres for a total of 13140 capsid proteins.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to drive movement along a single- or double-stranded RNA molecule.

label.value: DNA translocase activity involved in viral DNA genome packaging

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to drive movement along a single- or double-stranded DNA molecule, that contributes to the packing of viral DNA into a capsid.

label.value: RNA translocase activity involved in viral RNA genome packaging

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to drive movement along a single- or double-stranded RNA molecule, which contributes to the packaging of viral RNA into a nucleocapsid.
The lipid bilayer of a virion contained inside the protein capsid.
The region of a virion in which the nucleic acid is confined.
The region of a host cell that contains the viral genome.

label.value: suppression by virus of host NF-kappaB transcription factor activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host NF-kappaB activity.

label.value: suppression by virus of host poly(A)-binding protein activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of host poly(A)-binding protein (PABP) activity. PABP binds to the poly(A) tail of mRNA to facilitate translation.

label.value: activation by virus of host NF-kappaB transcription factor activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus starts, promotes, or enhances the activity of the host transcription factor NF-kappaB.

label.value: suppression by virus of host transcription

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host DNA-dependent transcription -  the cellular synthesis of RNA on a template of DNA. Viral proteins can interfere with either host RNA polymerase or with transcription factors.

label.value: modulation by virus of host gene expression

definition.value: The process in which a virus effects a change in gene expression in its host organism. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

label.value: suppression by virus of host gene expression

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression in the host organism. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.
A protein complex containing TBK1 (TANK-binding kinase 1), IKBKE (I-Kappa-B kinase epsilon|IKKE|IKK-epsilon) and the DEAD box family RNA helicase DDX3.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a virion.
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing in a cellular organelle, lipid bilayer of an organelle envelope, occurring in a host cell.
A lipid bilayer that forms the outermost layer of the cell envelope, occurring in a host cell.
A turret-like appendage formed at the vertices of an icosahedral capsid.

A crystalline protein matrix surrounding the nucleocapsids of some insect viruses after their release in the environment. Produced in the host cell, the occlusion body protects the infectious virion after death of the host.
The continuation of translation of a viral mRNA beyond a stop codon by the use of a special tRNA that recognizes the UAG and UGA codons as modified amino acids, rather than as termination codons.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a coreceptor. A coreceptor acts in cooperation with a primary receptor to transmit a signal within the cell.

An intracellular compartment in a host cell which increases the efficiency of viral replication and|or assembly, and shields the virus from host defenses. Viral factories can be either cytoplasmic or nuclear and often arise from extensive rearrangement of host cell cytoskeletal and|or cell membrane compartments.
A viral factory located in the cytoplasm of a host cell.
A viral factory located in the nucleus of a host cell.

A cytoplasmic viral factory that is electron dense due to high levels of viral RNA. Produced by nucleo-cytoplasmic large DNA viruses (NCLDV) like Poxviridae, Asfarviridae and Iridoviridae, and dsRNA viruses like Reoviridae.
A cytoplasmic viral factory which is a 50-400nm diameter membrane invagination. Spherules can appear on several enveloped cellular components depending on the virus.

A cytoplasmic viral factory that consists of a double-membrane bound vesicle. Has a diameter of 200-300nm and is derived from the endoplasmic reticulum or Golgi apparatus. Produced by Picornaviridae, Nidovirales, Arteriviridae and Coronaviridae.

A cytoplasmic viral factory derived from the Golgi in which Bunyaviridae replication takes place. Tubes are membranous structures close to the assembly and budding sites, and their function may be to connect viral replication and morphogenesis inside viral factories.
A nuclear viral factory formed by Baculoviruses. A vesicular structure in which virions are assembled.
A nuclear viral factory formed at the periphery of the host cell nucleus by Baculoviruses.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression -  the process is mitotically or meiotically heritable, or is stably self-propagated in the cytoplasm of a resting cell, and does not entail a change in DNA sequence.
Any process, mediated by small non-coding RNAs, that stops, prevents or reduces the rate that mRNAs are effectively translated into protein.
